# Rust Doesn't Have a Garbage Collector

This is a common misconception worth addressing directly. **Rust has no garbage collector** — this is actually one of its defining features and primary selling points.

---

## How Rust Manages Memory

Rust uses a compile-time ownership system instead of runtime garbage collection.

### Core Concepts

**Ownership Rules:**
- Every value has exactly one owner
- When the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped (freed) immediately
- No runtime overhead, no pauses

```rust
fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello"); // s owns this heap allocation

    do_something(s);               // ownership MOVES to the function

    // println!("{}", s);          // COMPILE ERROR: s no longer valid here
}                                  // if s still owned here, it would drop automatically

fn do_something(s: String) {
    println!("{}", s);
}   // s drops here, memory freed immediately
```

**Borrowing — Use Without Taking Ownership:**
```rust
fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello");

    print_length(&s);  // lend a reference, don't give ownership

    println!("{}", s); // s still valid here
}

fn print_length(s: &String) {  // borrows s, doesn't own it
    println!("Length: {}", s.len());
}   // reference dropped, but s is NOT freed (we don't own it)
```

**Borrow Rules (enforced at compile time):**
```rust
let mut s = String::from("hello");

let r1 = &s;      // immutable borrow - OK
let r2 = &s;      // second immutable borrow - OK
// let r3 = &mut s; // COMPILE ERROR: can't mutate while immutably borrowed

println!("{} {}", r1, r2);
// r1 and r2 no longer used after this point

let r3 = &mut s;  // mutable borrow - OK now
r3.push_str(" world");
```

